'''Vincent van Gogh''' was a Dutch Post-Impressionist painter whose work, notable for its bold colors and dramatic brushwork, contributed substantially to the foundations of modern art. He produced around 2,100 artworks during a career that lasted just over a decade, including some 860 oil paintings, most made in the final two years of his life.

Van Gogh struggled with mental illness and lived in poverty for much of his career, achieving little commercial success during his lifetime. He died in 1890, and his reputation grew posthumously, helped by the tireless advocacy of his sister-in-law Johanna van Gogh-Bonger.
